{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656882"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:19:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18772"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.1,0.72,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80321"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11504"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7113"},{"type":"tags","id":"7132"},{"type":"tags","id":"10362"},{"type":"tags","id":"10366"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe thalamus consists of paired nuclei within the diencephalon that process neural signals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the thalamus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maintains metabolic homeostasis","Secretes regulatory hormones","Processes and filters sensory information","Stores emotional experiences","Controls skeletal muscle activity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the thalamus is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprocess and filter sensory information\u003C/strong\u003E. It receives input from sensory pathways and modulates these signals before they reach cortical regions. This filtering mechanism prevents overwhelming of higher centers and enables focused attention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains metabolic homeostasis\u003C/strong\u003E - The hypothalamus regulates metabolism, temperature and appetite\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretes regulatory hormones\u003C/strong\u003E - Hormone production is controlled by the hypothalamus and pituitary\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls skeletal muscle activity\u003C/strong\u003E - Motor control involves the motor cortex, cerebellum and basal ganglia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStores emotional experiences\u003C/strong\u003E - The limbic system, particularly the amygdala and hippocampus, process emotions and memories\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe thalamus functions as a critical processing center, receiving and modulating nearly all sensory information (except olfactory signals) en route to the cerebral cortex. It also helps regulate consciousness through connections with the reticular system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The thalamus processes and filters incoming sensory signals before they reach higher brain centers.","Consciousness and arousal states are modulated by thalamic connections with the reticular formation.","Olfactory information is unique as the only sensory pathway that bypasses thalamic processing."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65590"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T13:15:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T13:16:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11504"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80321"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10